= Mechanical Sub-Harmonics

In the pitch domain, the first sub-harmonic of a tone (the tone to which our
tone is the first harmonic) is one octave below, which means half the frequency.
In the rhythm domain this would translate to half the speed:

 #figure(
  image("Figures/subharmonics-a.png"),
)

When we consider straight subdivisions, halving the speed is equivalent to
selecting every second accent. So in the rhythm domain, sub-harmonics of a
subdivision rate can be obtained by grouping those subdivisions: two-grouping
equals the first sub-harmonic, three-grouping the second, and so forth:

 #figure(
  image("Figures/subharmonics-b.png")
)

We call this the *mechanical sub-harmonic*.

When applied to swinging subdivisions, mechanical sub-harmonics render a rhythm
that is at first not foreseen, or pre-heard, with the potential of a _banana
skin_ effect (see Week 4) for the performer:

 #figure(
  image("Figures/subharmonics-c.png")
)
